<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lasthenia fremontii </i>is an annual composite that is endemic to the Central Valley. It has yellow ray flowers and opposite, linear to linear-lobed leaves. <i>L. fremontii </i>is pollinated by a specialist solitary bee that nests underground and emerges during the brief spring season when the plant blooms. The beeâ€™s life cycle is timed closely with the plantâ€™s reproductive cycle, which ensures the bee has pollen for food and the flower exchanges genetic material in pollen to produce seeds (Thorp 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Distichlis spicata </i>is a rhizomatous, warm-season grass that grows across most of temperate North America. Its physiological adaptations allow it to occupy saline environments. Plants contain salt glands that are active in the extrusion of salt and maintain adequate osmotic potentials. Lacunae tissue of the roots, rhizomes, and leaf sheath allow for gas exchange when in inundated soils. Plants produce little seed annually, but seeds accumulate in the soil. Seeds require high temperature, low salinity, and moist soil to germinate. Once established, plants grow in soils that vary greatly in salinity (Uchytil 1990f). <br/>
<br/>
Barbour et al. (2003, 2007b) recognized the <i>Downingia-Lasthenia </i>class of California vernal pool vegetation on all geomorphic surfaces, landscapes, and soil types in the Central Valley and adjacent foothills. Within that class, they recognized the <i>Frankenia salina - Lasthenia fremontii </i>alliance for the vegetation of shallow, alkaline, or saline vernal pools and playas. We have renamed this alliance as <i>Lasthenia fremontii - Distichlis spicata </i>in concert with Barbour et al. (2008). Most pools are typically large, flooded for long periods, and have shallow groundwater tables. Unlike other vernal pools with similar species composition, they also have perennial halophytes. They are inundated until the late spring with growth taking place later in the season (Barbour et al. 2007b). Rare taxa in this alliance include low constancy of <i>Astragalus tener </i>var. <i>tener, Atriplex persistens, Downingia pusilla, Gratiola heterosepala, Legenere limosa, </i>and <i>Orcuttia pilosa </i>(all CNPS 1B or 2 list plants). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
