    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aj-k, Aq, At, Av-w, Ay). Stands of the <i>Downingia insignis-Psilocarphus brevissimus</i> association appear as the most common, widely distributed association of this alliance within the Sacramento Valley. Defined within this association are three subassociations with <i>Eleocharis acicularis, Grindelia camporum,</i> and <i>Lagophylla</i> spp. the diagnostic species. The following associations occur in the Solano-Colusa region (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998a), including Jepson Prairie. Stands of the <i>Lasthenia glaberrima-Atriplex persistens</i> association are relatively uncommon in large pools in that region. Stands of the <i>Limnanthes douglasii- Pleuropogon californicus</i> association is a common edge type, forming distinctive white bands that surround patches of golden-yellow pool bottoms of the <i>Lasthenia fremontii-Pleuropogon californicus</i> association. Stands of the <i>Lasthenia platycarpha-Lepidium latipes</i> association exist in large, shallow, short-inundated pools at Gridley Ranch and Jepson Prairie. Stands of the <i>Downingia pulchella-Cressa truxillensis</i> association and the related Downingia pulchella-Distichlis spicata association are relatively common in moderately small pools in the San Joaquin Valley. Those of the <i>Hordeum depressum/leporinum</i> type lack many diagnostic species, except for <i>Cressa truxillenisis</i> and <i>Distichlis spicata,</i> occurring as a derivate type at Pixley Ranch (Barbour et al. 2007b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd). Stands of the <i>Downingia bella-Hemizonia pungens, Downingia bella-Lilaea scilloides,</i> and <i>Downingia cuspidata-Myosurus minimus</i> associations are relatively uncommon in small to very small pools in the southern subsection (Barbour et al. 2007b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Alkaline pools in cismontane California are depleted severely in number and extent. Threats are primarily from loss of habitat due to conversion to agriculture and development. However, threats also include non-native plants, including the salt-tolerant <i>Cotula coronopifolia, Crypsis schoenoides, Cynodon dactylon, Erodium </i>spp., <i>Hordeum leporinum, Lolium perenne, Medicago polymorpha,  </i>and <i>Polypogon monspeliensis</i>. </div>
</div>

    

    

